s=​\"css-view-g5y9jx r-flex-13awgt0 r-bottom-1p0dtai r-left-1d2f490 r-position-u8s1d r-right-zchlnj r-top-ipm5af\" style=​\"background-color:​ rgb(242, 242, 242)​;​ display:​ flex;​\" aria-hidden=​\"true\">​…​</div>​Comprende esta advertencia',0.1685135530508752,'[\"\\\"baseurl\\\"\", \"\\\"foxitsymbol.pfb\\\"\", \"\\\"standardfontdataurl\\\"\", \"\\\"unknownerrorexception:\", \"->\"]','2025-11-29 17:06:17.108092'),(67,3,'Resumen ultra corto\n\nBackend (FastAPI + modelo + SQLite)\n? GitHub → Render Web Service\n? Comando: uvicorn app:app --host 0.0.0.0 --port $PORT\n\nFrontend (Expo Web)\n? GitHub → Vercel\n? Build: npx expo export:web\n? Output: dist (o .expo/web/dist)\n? Env var: EXPO_PUBLIC_API_BASE = URL_DEL_BACKEND',0.2173332801294191,'[\"$port\", \"(expo\", \"(fastapi\", \"(o\", \"+\"]','2025-11-29 17:06:39.764064'),(68,3,'Avanzar con propósito no es correr sin dirección, sino mantener un ritmo consciente, equilibrado y motivador. Significa reconocer los desafíos, aprender de ellos y continuar fortalecidos. La clave está en recordar que cada día ofrece una nueva oportunidad para crecer, mejorar y reinventarnos.',0.15541937116718926,'[\"aprender\", \"avanzar\", \"cada\", \"clave\", \"con\"]','2025-11-29 17:07:11.716090'),(69,3,'Tomarse un momento para reflexionar, organizar ideas y decidir el siguiente movimiento permite que nuestras acciones tengan sentido. La disciplina transforma las intenciones en resultados, y la constancia convierte esos resultados en hábitos duraderos. Así, poco a poco, construimos el camino hacia nuestras propias metas.',0.20101253753260487,'[\"a\", \"acciones\", \"as\\u00ed,\", \"camino\", \"constancia\"]','2025-11-29 17:07:19.500338'),(70,3,'uestra vida. Cada meta, por pequeña que parezca, representa un paso firme hacia un futuro mejor.',0.16577043008074793,'[\"cada\", \"firme\", \"futuro\", \"hacia\", \"mejor.\"]','2025-11-29 17:07:39.624322'),(71,3,'ORIGINAL RESEARCH  Health consumers ’   ethical concerns towards arti fi cial intelligence in Australian emergency departments  Sam FREEMAN   ,   1,2   Jonathon STEWART   ,   3,4   Rebecca KAARD, 5   Eden OULIEL,   5   Adrian GOUDIE,   6,3 Girish DWIVEDI 3,4,7   and Hamed AKHLAGHI   1  1   Department of Emergency Medicine, St Vincent ’ s Hospital, Melbourne, Victoria, Australia,   2   Centre for Digital Transformation of Health, The University of Melbourne, Melbourne, Victoria, Australia,   3   School of Medicine, The University of Western Australia, Perth, Western Australia, Australia,   4 Cardiovascular Disease and Diabetes Program, Harry Perkins Institute of Medical Research, Perth, Western Australia, Australia, 5   School of Medicine, The University of Notre Dame, Fremantle, Western Australia, Australia,   6   Department of Emergency Medicine, Fiona Stanley Hospital, Perth, Western Australia, Australia, and   7   Department of Cardiology, Fiona Stanley Hospital, Perth, Western Australia, Australia  Abstract  Objectives : To investigate health con- sumers ’   ethical concerns towards the use of arti fi cial intelligence (AI) in EDs.  Methods : Qualitative   semi-structured interviews with health consumers, rec- ruited via health consumer networks and   community   groups,   interviews conducted   between   January   and August 2022.  Results : We   interviewed   28   health consumers   about   their   perceptions towards the ethical use of AI in EDs. The   results   discussed   in   this   paper highlight the challenges and barriers for   the   effective   and   ethical   imple- mentation of AI from the perspective of Australian health consumers. Most health consumers are more likely to support AI health tools in EDs if they continue   to   be   involved   in   the decision-making   process.   There   is considerably   more   approval   of   AI tools that support clinical decision- making,   as   opposed   to   replacing it. There is mixed sentiment about the acceptability of AI tools in fl uencing clinical   decision-making   and   judge- ment. Health consumers are mostly supportive of the use of their data to train and develop AI tools but are concerned   with   who   has   access. Addressing bias and discrimination in AI is an important consideration for some health consumers. Robust regu- lation and governance are critical for health consumers to trust and accept the use of AI.  Conclusion : Health consumers view AI as an emerging technology that they   want   to   see   comprehensively regulated to ensure it functions safely and securely with EDs. Without con- siderations   made   for   the   ethical design,   implementation   and   use   of AI   technologies,   health   consumer trust and acceptance in the use of these tools will be limited.  Key   words:   arti fi cial   intelligence, emergency   medicine,   ethics,   health consumers, machine learning, quali- tative research.  Introduction  Advancements   in   arti fi cial   intelli- gence (AI) are predicted to impact healthcare delivery in a multitude of ways such as providing a comprehen- sive   picture   of   an   individual ’ s healthcare   data,   augmenting   clinical decision-making,   reducing   diagnostic errors, assisting with test selection and interpretation, and recommending fur- ther   management   options. 1   Despite the technology behind most of these advances continuing to improve, par- ticularly   through   machine   learning (ML), 2   there remain key challenges in the Australian health system that need Correspondence: Dr Sam Freeman, Department of Emergency Medicine, St Vincent ’ s Hospital, Melbourne, VIC, Australia. Email: sam.freeman@svha.org.au Sam Freeman, PhD, Research Fellow; Jonathon Stewart, MBBS, MMed(CritCare), Anaesthetic Registrar; Rebecca Kaard, MBBS Student; Eden Ouliel, MBBS Student; Adrian Goudie, MBBS FACEM DDU, Emergency Physician; Girish Dwivedi, MD, PhD, FRACP, Wesfarmers Chair and Consultant Cardiologist; Hamed Akhlaghi, MD, PhD, FACEM, Emergency Physician, Head of Emergency Medicine Research. This is an open access article under the terms of the Creative Commons Attribution- NonCommercial-NoDerivs   License,   which   permits   use   and   distribution   in   any medium, provided the original work is properly cited, the use is non-commercial and no modi fi cations or adaptations are made.  Accepted 15 May 2024  Key   fi ndings  •   Health   consumers   generally support   arti fi cial   intelligence (AI) tools that assist clinicians in   decision-making   but   are wary of tools replacing doc- tors, with trust diminishing as AI ’ s   decision-making   auton- omy increases.  •   Health   consumers   express   a strong   desire   to   be   actively involved in AI-driven decision- making about their healthcare in emergency settings.  •   Mixed sentiments surround the acceptability of AI in fl uencing doctor   decision-making,   with concerns about its impact on healthcare quality. Health con- sumers fear a short-term under- mining of nurses and doctors, leading to a potential reduction in clinical skills and a long-term shift   towards   ‘ box-ticking ’  exercises,   raising   discomfort and   scepticism   about   the technology ’ s role in emergency medicine. © 2024 The Author(s).   Emergency Medicine Australasia   published by John Wiley & Sons Australia, Ltd on behalf of Australasian College for Emergency Medicine.  Emergency Medicine Australasia   (2024)   36 , 768 – 776   doi: 10.1111/1742-6723.14449\nurgent   attention.   These   include   an increasing demand for healthcare ser- vices, an ageing population, increas- ing   costs   associated   with   medical research and innovations and grow- ing rates of chronic disease. 3   This has led groups such as policymakers, pol- iticians,   technology   companies   and data scientists to advocate for AI to address these challenges. 4 It is predicted that the use of AI- based tools will become increasingly common in EDs. 5   However, there is limited published research that qualita- tively assesses how health consumers (people who use health services, their families and carers) feel about AI use in their care in an ED context. To date, research has mostly focused on health consumers ’   perceptions of AI in speci fi c sub fi elds of medicine, such as radiology, dermatology, general prac- tice and primary care. This   paper   presents   health   con- sumer attitudes towards AI to help inform future research and highlight risk   mitigation   strategies   for   the effective and ethical implementation of AI in EDs.  Methods  Study design and setting  This qualitative study was designed in accordance with the consolidated criteria   for   reporting   qualitative research.   6   We   developed   a   semi- structured interview guide based on the review of existing literature and input from the multidisciplinary pro- ject   team.   Members   of   the   project team   have   recognised   expertise   in emergency medicine, qualitative resea- rch   and   AI   and   also   included   two healthcare   consumer   representatives. The   study   protocol   and   interview guide were presented to and received formal support from the Fiona Stanley Hospital Emergency Department Con- sumer   Advisory   Group   (Western Australia). We conducted three pilot interviews and re fi ned the   interview guide based on feedback. Twenty-eight   semi-structured interviews were conducted between January and August 2022 to assess health   consumers ’   perspectives   and considerations for the ethical imple- mentation   and   use   of   AI   in   EDs. Participants were recruited from dif- ferent health consumer networks and community   groups,   including   the Consumer Community Involvement Program (Western Australia), Fiona Stanley Hospital Emergency Depart- ment   Consumer   Advisory   Group (Western   Australia),   St   Vincent ’ s Hospital   Melbourne   Human Research   Ethics   Committee   layper- son members (Victoria), Health Con- sumers   Queensland   (Queensland) and the Centre for Culture, Ethnic- ity & Health (Australia wide), where recruitment details were distributed through its members and networks. The interviews were conducted until thematic saturation (de fi ned as three consecutive interviews with no new themes identi fi ed) was achieved. This research utilises a grounded theory approach,   which   was   selected because it provides a methodology for collecting and analysing data and conceptualising   the   results.   7   Inter- views were conducted by telephone via a voice call (without video) and audio   recorded.   Audio   fi les   were de-identi fi ed and professionally tran- scribed by a secure transcription ser- vice.   Interviews   were   conducted   in Australia with participants from New South   Wales,   Queensland,   Victoria and Western Australia. For a further breakdown   of   participant   demo- graphics (see Table 1).  Participant selection  A convenience sample was used to recruit   respondents   ( n   =   28)   based on   accessibility   and   willingness   to take part in the study.   8  Data collection  Semi-structured   interviews   were   con- ducted with additional questions and prompts used as needed. Although the discussion of ethical concerns was led by respondents, prompts included prin- ciples such as consent, transparency, privacy, safety and harm, bias, fairness and   redress.   There   were   no   repeat interviews or transcription checks by participants. Interview duration ranged from 10 to 45 min.  Data analysis  Two investigators (SF and JS) indepen- dently analysed and coded interviews using open coding techniques based on grounded theory.   All   the   interviews were coded using NVivo 20 (QSR, Melbourne,   Australia).   Codes   and themes were iteratively developed and re fi ned until most content was able to be classi fi ed. Agreement on codes and themes was reached at researcher meet- ings where differing codes were dis- cussed and a consensus on their coding was agreed upon.  Characteristics of interviewers  The interviews were conducted by SF, two medical students (RK and EO), and an ED Registrar. Interviews were held over the phone without video to reduce any bias that the interviewer ’ s appearance may have on responses. The interviewers had no prior rela- tionship with the study participants.  Characteristics of research team  At   the   time   of   conducting   this research   SF   was   a   PhD   candidate  TABLE   1.   Participant   demo- graphic information  Category   n   % Sex Female   17   61 Male   10   36 Non-binary   1   4 Age group 20 – 29   2   7 30 – 39   6   21 40 – 49   6   21 50 – 59   2   7 60 – 69   2   7 70 – 79   10   36 Location New South Wales   1   4 Queensland   5   18 Victoria   14   50 Western Australia   8   29 © 2024 The Author(s).   Emergency Medicine Australasia   published by John Wiley & Sons Australia, Ltd on behalf of Australasian College for Emergency Medicine. ETHICAL ARTIFICIAL INTELLIGENCE IN EMERGENCY CARE   769 17426723, 2024, 5, Downloaded from https://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/10.1111/1742-6723.14449 by Cochrane Peru, Wiley Online Library on [15/04/2025]. See the Terms and Conditions (https://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/terms-and-conditions) on Wiley Online Library for rules of use; OA articles are governed by the applicable Creative Commons License\n(focus on ethical implementation of AI in emergency medicine) and a research fellow at an Australian ED. JS was a PhD candidate (focus on applications of AI in emergency medicine) and an emergency medicine trainee. RK and EO   were   both   second-year   medical students who had not completed rota- tions in emergency medicine.  Ethical considerations  The study received University of West- ern Australia Research Ethics Commit- tee   approval   (2021/ET000609). Informed consent was gained from all respondents participating in the present study. The present study was prospec- tively   registered   with   the   Australian New Zealand Clinical Trials Registry (ACTRN12621000890831).  Results  The results provide an overview of health   consumers ’   key   perceptions of ethical AI in an ED setting. Key ethical   concerns   presented   here include health consumer autonomy and consent, doctor decision-making and autonomy, automation bias and reliance, data usage and privacy, bias and discrimination and regulation.  Health consumer autonomy and consent  Most   health   consumers   are   more likely to support AI health tools in emergency medicine if they continue to   be   involved   in   the   decision- making   process   about   their   health and can still understand why a treat- ment recommendation or diagnosis is made. There is some concern that with   the   use   of   increasingly   adva- nced technologies, they will no lon- ger be able to ask questions or have key issues explained to them about their treatment or diagnosis. For many participants there is a requirement to have the role of AI in their treatment explained to them at the   earliest   opportunity.   Many believe they would be more comfort- able with the use of AI if it is effec- tively   communicated.   This   becomes even more important with the incre- ased   complexity   or   risk   associated with the function of the AI tool. This is particularly important if the role of AI includes clinical decision support that relates to differential   diagnosis, complex cases, serious health condi- tions or decisions that were tradition- ally tasked to doctors and nurses. Effective   communication   is   criti- cally important to most health con- sumers   to   improve   autonomy   and consent processes. Many already feel that   information   in   EDs   could   be better communicated and that if AI is to play a future role in emergency medicine, in any capacity, it needs to be clearly communicated. The more  ‘ serious ’   the concern or high-risk set- ting   the   tool   is   functioning   in,   the more information consumers require. There is concern that AI systems may be non-interpretable by the doc- tor,   meaning   the   doctor   may   be unable   to   effectively   understand results and subsequently communi- cate   them   to   their   patients.   This thereby impacts the patient ’ s ability to give informed consent. There are mixed views, however, about the type and amount of informa- tion required, and how it is communi- cated.   Overwhelmingly,   consumers want to know (to varying degrees) if an   AI   tool   is   being   used   in   their healthcare pathway. If an AI tool is used in a patient ’ s healthcare   pathway   and   they   were not   informed,   many   report   they would   feel   ‘ betrayed ’ ,   ‘ annoyed ’ ,  ‘ frustrated ’   or   ‘ distressed ’ . For trust and   acceptance   of   these   systems, many health consumers believe that improved   consent   processes   are needed to ensure the risks, bene fi ts and alternatives can be explained in how the tool works and that they have the opportunity to opt in or out of   having   the   tool   used   in   their healthcare delivery. There is fear that the introduction of these tools will lead to a loss of human connection in the ED, in par- ticular   empathy   and   sympathy,   in what is for many people an already highly stressful environment. Some see the   healthcare   journey   as   a   human experience and want it delivered with kindness and compassion   –   traits not typically   associated   with   AI   and machines. Having that human connec- tion in a health setting is not only con- sidered   important   on   an   emotional, human   level,   but   also   connects   to health consumer autonomy.  Doctor decision-making and autonomy  There is considerably more approval for AI tools in the ED that support cli- nician decision-making, as opposed to replacing   it.   Most   participants   will only support these tools if their func- tion is subsidiary to the role of the doctor. Trust and acceptance and AI decision-making autonomy appear to have an inverse relationship. As an AI tool ’ s   decision-making   autonomy increases in the ED, patient trust and acceptance decrease. There is recognition that   human decision-making   is   fallible, particu- larly in a dynamic, complex ED envi- ronment.   Against   this   backdrop, participants see potential in AI tools being   used   to   support   doctor   and nurse   decision-making.   For   some, there is also an expectation that AI tools will likely make mistakes. For many, it is how these mistakes are responded   to   that   will   determine their level of acceptance. The   doctor   is   predominantly viewed as the   fi nal authority regard- ing   patients ’   health.   Trust   and acceptability in AI tools are derived from the doctor agreeing with the AI tools ’   prediction. When respondents envisage an AI tool operating inde- pendently of doctor oversight, many health   consumers   said   they   would insist on being treated by a doctor if they disagreed with the decision of the AI health tool. For some, no mat- ter what scenario occurs within the ED, clinicians are considered more accurate in diagnosing and treating patients. Although there are differing views about the acceptability of AI tools   to   make   errors,   ultimately, most health consumers hold AI tools to   a   higher   standard   of   accuracy than ED doctors and nurses. Despite concerns about the effec- tiveness and accuracy of AI, some health   consumers   state   that   once these   tools   are   ‘ proven ’   to   out- perform   doctors   then   they   would prefer AI tools over doctors. Some health   consumers   state   that   in some circumstances, they would prefer AI-assisted   decision-making,   such   as © 2024 The Author(s).   Emergency Medicine Australasia   published by John Wiley & Sons Australia, Ltd on behalf of Australasian College for Emergency Medicine.  770   S FREEMAN   ET AL. 17426723, 2024, 5, Downloaded from https://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/10.1111/1742-6723.14449 by Cochrane Peru, Wiley Online Library on [15/04/2025]. See the Terms and Conditions (https://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/terms-and-conditions) on Wiley Online Library for rules of use; OA articles are governed by the applicable Creative Commons License\nwhen a doctor is overworked, the ED is short-staffed or overcrowded, or the treating clinician has limited experi- ence   in   the   role.   Health   consumers largely   accept   that   their   perceptions may change with advancements in AI technology and its predicted increased integration into healthcare. However, doctors are still regarded as providing the   preferred standard of care   over any form of AI tool.  Automation bias and reliance  There   is   mixed   sentiment   among respondents about the acceptability of AI tools in fl uencing ED doctors ’  decision-making and clinical judge- ment. Many were concerned that AI tools would in fl uence doctors ’   judge- ment   and   impact   the   quality   of healthcare   provision.   For   these health consumers, AI is considered just another tool to be utilised by cli- nicians and should not be afforded special   status   over   any   other   tool available in the ED. If AI tools are believed to have an in fl uential role over   clinical   decision-making,   it would   make   health   consumers  ‘ uncomfortable ’ ,   ‘ sceptical ’   and   ‘ dis- trustful ’   of the technology. Many health consumers are con- cerned that the use of AI tools in emergency medicine will result in a reliance on them. In the short term, consumers   feel   these   tools   could undermine   the   role   of   nurses   and doctors   within   the   ED   and   in   the long term could reduce the skills and ability of clinicians. There is a belief from some that diagnosing patients and clinical judgement will become  ‘ box ticking ’   exercises, where a clini- cian ’ s   ‘ gut   feeling ’ ,   ‘ intuition ’   and  ‘ instincts ’   are   no   longer   attributes that are developed and valued.  Data usage and privacy  Health   consumers   are   mostly   sup- portive of the use of their data to train and support the development of AI tools in emergency medicine but   are   concerned   with   who   has access.   Most   are   comfortable   with their non-identi fi able data being used for healthcare purposes, but only for healthcare purposes. If it was later dis- covered   that   their   information   had been used outside of the healthcare system,   or   for   purposes   other   than improving   healthcare   delivery   or healthcare research, trust and accep- tance of these tools would diminish. There   is   concern   about   data breaches and the level of security for protecting personal health informa- tion. However, many are aware of the inherent risks involved in sharing and   storing   data.   Although   it   is recognised   that   privacy   issues   are not unique to AI, many want assur- ances that their data is being handled securely. Many state that they are not   overly   concerned   about   their own   medical   data   being   released publicly, but do recognise that some health information and some mem- bers of the public could be negatively impacted, targeted or discriminated against based on their health data: Some   health   consumers   want greater control over the health infor- mation   that   is   shared   and   stored. Many   want   consent   processes   in place, so they are aware if the infor- mation is being shared and have the ability to opt in or out of its collec- tion and sharing. There are privacy concerns about how data will be col- lected in the ED if managed by an AI-enabled   platform.   Some   partici- pants   are   apprehensive   about   how patient-to-machine   information   will be communicated in a crowded ED environment.   Some   discussed   the need for a private space to feel com- fortable sharing information.  Bias and discrimination  Addressing bias and discrimination in AI is an important consideration for some   health   consumers.   There   is concern that AI will inherit the same biases   that   are   already   present   in healthcare. One participant feels that having come from a Caucasian back- ground   means   that   AI   tools   will likely be accurate for them, but less accurate or reliable for people from culturally   and   linguistically   diverse backgrounds. There are concerns that AI tools will bias or discriminate against cul- turally   and   linguistically   diverse populations,   First   Nations   people, women   and   people   with   disability and   complex   medical   needs.   Bias and discrimination are linked to per- ceptions of accuracy. For health con- sumers   to   trust   and   accept   these tools in the ED, they must be con- vinced they are accurate. Part of that required accuracy is how well they perform   for   people   from   multicul- tural backgrounds. It will be impor- tant   that   AI   based   tools   do   not perpetuate existing biases or intro- duce new biases.  Regulation  Regulation   is   an   important   aspect for trusting and accepting the use of AI   in   EDs   for   health   consumers. Some health consumers want assur- ances that there is robust regulation and oversight in the design, develop- ment, training and ongoing use of these tools. Most support a govern- ment   regulatory   body   to   establish guidelines   and   oversee   compliance. Some   see   this   as   the   role   of   the national government to ensure con- sistency across states and territories. Many do not want to see industry self-regulation   or   regulation   and standards left to the private sector. Here, there is concern that pro fi t will be   the   motivating   factor   for   the implementation   and   use   of   these tools, not improving patient health outcomes. Some   health   consumers   want   to see   more   localised   governance   and accountability of these tools such as the hospital administration or industry peak   bodies   such   as   the   Australian Medical Association, to ensure train- ing and policies are established and provided at the clinical level. There are also calls for AI tools to be endorsed by the bodies that represent the medi- cal professionals who are required to use these tools in clinical practice. Some health consumers also want these tools to pass through an ethics review   process.   For   these   respon- dents, it is not enough to just con- sider the safety and medical accuracy of these tools, it must also consider their ethical impact (Table 2).  Discussion  This research found that health con- sumer   acceptance   of   AI-enabled health tools requires the consideration © 2024 The Author(s).   Emergency Medicine Australasia   published by John Wiley & Sons Australia, Ltd on behalf of Australasian College for Emergency Medicine. ETHICAL ARTIFICIAL INTELLIGENCE IN EMERGENCY CARE   771 17426723, 2024, 5, Downloaded from https://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/10.1111/1742-6723.14449 by Cochrane Peru, Wiley Online Library on [15/04/2025]. See the Terms and Conditions (https://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/terms-and-conditions) on Wiley Online Library for rules of use; OA articles are governed by the applicable Creative Commons License\nTABLE 2.   Sample comments by health consumers on ethical concerns  Qualitative dimension   Sub-dimension   Example quote Patient autonomy and consent Health consumer understanding of treatment or diagnosis  … that I was involved in the discussions about my treatment, patients being encouraged to be involved in decision-making about their care, that actually has to be absolutely central to the whole process still so that I wouldn ’ t want the human element and the capacity for me as a patient to actually explain my concerns and, you know, the capacity of me to ask questions. Effective communication that AI is being used I think as a patient I would also want to understand the role of AI in the whole process, and I think that would be very, very important because if I found out for some reason, you know, at a later date that (that AI was being used), that would be quite disturbing. But I think if I was involved at the start in knowing that this system was actually helping clinicians to arrive at an accurate diagnosis, I think I would be very satis fi ed, very comfortable with that. You ’ ve got to have that communication, break that barrier to communication face-to-face by someone who can explain what ’ s happening. Amount of information health consumers require  … not in a great amount of detail, but it would just be nice to have that reassurance. The more information, the better. Consent requirements With my consent, I ’ d feel good about it. I think you need to opt in. Doctor – patient relationship I wouldn ’ t like it because you want to be heard and seen by a compassionate, kind professional. This is a human experience, and I don ’ t want it to be determined by a robot. At least, if the robot has this decision, I would want a human sitting there and explaining it to me …   the desperation and feeling unwell, just to be questioned by a robot in a yes or no or to get an answer way, it ’ s going to just increase the frustration and the suffering, I feel. Doctor decision- making and autonomy AI errors in decision-making  … every human body is different so the program is written for the majority, allowing for some differences, but there ’ ll always be individuals that   … swim against the   fl ow and where they should have got better, all the signs are there that they should have got better and something has happened, but that happens just when a doctor sends them home, the fact that it ’ s a computer algorithm that did the agree-to-release, in my eyes, makes no difference. AI accuracy   If it replaces something that ’ s there at the moment, yes, it has to be better.   … I can imagine that 15 years down the track I would see it as completely irrelevant, but I think during a new kind of introductory phase of a new technology, I think it would be perceived as far worse for a computer to make an error. Because I think if it ’ s proven to be more failsafe and make less mistakes than what the humans are performing then I would take my chances with that over human assessment for sure. AI over doctors   I mean not every doctor ’ s going to be a specialist in every   fi eld. And in emergency, the guy treating me may not be the most capable guy in whatever it is I have. [So] I think the fact that he can rely on the information from a tool to help him in the diagnostics would be very useful. Automation bias and reliance AI in fl uence over doctor decision- making Well, I would think it ’ s actually a slap in the face to doctors, because you ’ re negating all the experience that they ’ ve had, and their own experience will tell them a lot of information that the machine can ’ t gather. © 2024 The Author(s).   Emergency Medicine Australasia   published by John Wiley & Sons Australia, Ltd on behalf of Australasian College for Emergency Medicine.  772   S FREEMAN   ET AL. 17426723, 2024, 5, Downloaded from https://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/10.1111/1742-6723.14449 by Cochrane Peru, Wiley Online Library on [15/04/2025]. See the Terms and Conditions (https://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/terms-and-conditions) on Wiley Online Library for rules of use; OA articles are governed by the applicable Creative Commons License\nand minimisation of ethical issues. As AI research continues to develop it is important   to   understand   what   are considered   by   healthcare   consumers to be acceptable uses of the technol- ogy in emergency medicine contexts. These   results   provide   information about health consumers ’   current per- ceptions of AI in emergency medicine and further emphasises the need for effective   communication   to   ensure consumers understand the function of AI and the role it will play in the deliv- ery of their healthcare. Consumers require assurance that the   ED   doctor   retains   the   fi nal decision-making authority and that they understand how and why an AI tool has come to a certain prediction or   recommendation.   This   may   be challenging as current AI tools are for the most part   ‘ black boxes ’   with reasoning that is not interpretable to humans.   9 It appears that trust and acceptance of   AI   tools   and   clinician   decision- making   autonomy   are   inversely related.   The   more   autonomous   or independent the tool is from ED doc- tors ’   oversight   and   understanding, the less likely patients are to trust its output. There are reservations about the accuracy and performance of these technologies, and also apprehension about moving to a new standard of care, which may remove other ele- ments   of   healthcare   considered important to patients such as the doctor – patient   relationship.   Other research   into   patient   perspectives on   AI   in   different   medical   fi elds found comparable results   –   patients  TABLE 2.   Continued  Qualitative dimension   Sub-dimension   Example quote Reduced doctor skill and ability  … as soon as we start taking away decisions from health professionals, we ’ re sort of undermining their training and we start, look, it ’ s complicated because I think if we could take routine jobs away from nurses and doctors to help them focus on more important things, that would be great. But I ’ m worried that [they] would then start relying on AI and it would undermine the expertise of doctors and nurses. Data usage and privacy  Re -use of patient health consumer data If you ’ ve given consent for it, no problems. You wouldn ’ t want it to be then on-sold or used for anything else. I could understand people who are very private and would not want their medical records (shared) … . but as long as it ’ s unidenti fi ed and they ’ re not used for any other purpose, you know, it ’ s probably inevitable things are going down this track in all   fi elds. [Concern] around how your data ’ s kept and used, and the breaches   –   what ’ s being collected and how could that be used. Control over the sharing of health consumer data  … Patients should be able to consent to certain information being taken, and where that information is actually going to go. On the other hand, I really do support the interoperability of programs, so that they can talk to one another, after consent is received. How private data is disclosed It would depend on how the information was communicated, like if it was …  in an open space. You know, are people ’ s private health details being broadcast loud by this AI? Is it happening in a quiet, private space? Bias and discrimination AI and human bias   I don ’ t think AI is good enough yet and everyone ’ s just forging ahead with it, thinking it ’ s great and missing the fact that it ’ s really not great. It ’ s programmed like humans, so it will have human error in it. Discrimination and multicultural populations  … the (AI) system has been calibrated using data that isn ’ t particularly diverse and then the output it generates is biased because of that. Regulation   Government regulation I think it ’ s got to be a multi-layered approach. I think Australia at a federal level has to have some very clear guidelines around the use of AI in medical settings and lots of other settings, but if we ’ re just sticking with medical, I think we need to have some federal governance around that. Local governance mechanisms But I do think then we need to have local [governance], like AMA (Australia Medical Association) or state level or even hospital level to make sure that staff are trained, staff are upskilled, that there is a local connection with what ’ s going on federally. © 2024 The Author(s).   Emergency Medicine Australasia   published by John Wiley & Sons Australia, Ltd on behalf of Australasian College for Emergency Medicine. ETHICAL ARTIFICIAL INTELLIGENCE IN EMERGENCY CARE   773 17426723, 2024, 5, Downloaded from https://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/10.1111/1742-6723.14449 by Cochrane Peru, Wiley Online Library on [15/04/2025]. See the Terms and Conditions (https://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/terms-and-conditions) on Wiley Online Library for rules of use; OA articles are governed by the applicable Creative Commons License\nare much more likely to support AI if there is a human tasked with mak- ing   the   fi nal   decision   or recommendation. 10 – 15   In part, this is because there is more trust in the abil- ity of an experienced doctor. Doctors are also able to justify and explain their   decision   or   recommendation, something health consumers currently do not associate with AI technology. Many   patients   still   want   the human   connection   and   assurance healthcare staff provide when they are   going   through   a   potentially stressful   time,   something   machines are viewed as incapable of providing. However,   these   views   may   change with increased exposure to advanced AI tools. A recent study comparing physician and ChatGPT responses to patient questions found that patients rated ChatGPT responses   ‘ higher for both quality and empathy ’ . 16   With this challenging the assumptions of most health consumers that AI tools will lack empathy. Some of the lit- erature also suggests that patients fear losing human interaction from their   healthcare   delivery   and   are concerned   that   AI   tools   will   be unable   to   comprehend   emotional issues,   particularly   in   relation   to patients   experiencing   mental   ill- health.   10,11,14,17 – 19   This   concern appears   to   intensify   in   an   emer- gency   setting   with   patients   often requiring urgent medical attention, and where the human connection is considered especially important in reducing distress. Health   consumers   are   concerned about privacy and the use of their per- sonal   health   data.   Although   many approve   of   the   use   of   their   non- identi fi able   medical   data to   support the development of AI tools within healthcare,   they   are   still   concerned about   con fi dentiality   and   who   has access to it. This is consistent with research into patient perspectives of AI   in   radiology 20   and   healthcare chatbots, 17   which found patients are only willing to share data if it remains con fi dential and non-identi fi able. Con- sumers will likely rescind their support for data usage if it transpires that their personal   information   is   being   used outside of the healthcare system or for purposes other than improving patient health outcomes. Many   health   consumers   believe they are aware of the inherent risks involved in the sharing and storage of data. However, health consumers may be under the assumption that their health data refers only to data held by healthcare organisations in their health records. Yet, these data sources are considered only a small part of the   ‘ larger health data eco- system ’ . 21   This includes health data generated   by   non-healthcare   pro- viders such as insurance companies, non-health information where infer- ences   are   made   about   health,   and user-generated health data.   21   Health consumers may feel less comfortable knowing that there is the potential for this information to be collected and used to make decisions about them, particularly if used by com- mercial entities. Data collection and sharing policies need to be updated to ensure data collected and gener- ated through the use of these tools meets the standards and expectations of consumers. Most   health   consumers   see informed   consent   as   a   critical   ele- ment   in   gaining   their   trust   and acceptance regardless of the role AI might play in their treatment. One study   22   identi fi ed that informed con- sent   is   not   receiving   the   attention needed   in   the   ethical   debate   sur- rounding   AI   implementation,   with another study 23   reporting that   ‘ ubiq- uity, complexity and opaqueness ’   are major   contributors   to   health   con- sumers ’   ‘ inability to assess or predict outcomes   or   harms ’   associated with   the   use   of   AI   in   healthcare and   therefore   provide   informed consent. The issue of consent app- ears   to   be   a   signi fi cant   consider- ation for health consumers. It will be important that the ED doctors and hospital management who are tasked   with   implementing   these technologies   ensure   the   consent process is current and appropriate, and that the use of AI in the ED is communicated effectively. Addressing   bias   and   discrimina- tion that results from the introduc- tion   of   AI   is   important   to   many health   consumers.   However,   bias and discrimination pre-existent to AI is   not   without   precedent   in   the Australian healthcare system, where First   Nations   people   ‘ continue   to suffer   adverse   experiences   in healthcare, with inequitable care pre- valent   in   emergency   settings ’ . 24 Research   has   highlighted   that   the Australian   healthcare   system   under serves those from culturally and lin- guistically diverse backgrounds, 25   has discriminated   against   women 26   and people   with   disability. 27   For   AI   to bene fi t   diverse   populations   such   as Australia ’ s, the design and develop- ment of AI technologies must include input from diverse populations from diverse   geographic   locations,   who will   use   or   be   exposed   to   these technologies. 28 It appears that health consumers envisage a more rigorous regulatory framework that monitors and evalu- ates the design, development, imple- mentation and use of AI technologies than   currently   exists   within Australia. Although the Therapeutic Goods Administration does regulate software as a medical device, which AI software are categorised, there is no regulation that relates speci fi cally to these technologies.   29   Because of this   assumption,   it   is   likely   that future regulation and guidance will need to address issues of oversight and evaluation to gain the support of consumers. This will likely include ensuring health consumers are protec- ted,   and   that   improved   health   out- comes are a priority in implementing these systems. 29   This also relates to fears that AI tools may not be appro- priately   regulated   and   be   more in fl uenced by   fi nancial incentives than improving healthcare outcomes. The existing literature, similarly, found that rigorous regulation and guidance of AI in healthcare is regarded as impor- tant for protecting patient wellbeing, monitoring the safety of these systems, reducing   risks   to   patient   privacy, assessing   the   potential   for   systemic bias   embedded   in   AI   models   and enabling   continuous   system improvements. 29 – 31   Last, many emer- gency   physicians   share   similar   con- cerns about the use of AI in EDs as health   consumers.   These   common concerns include data usage and pri- vacy, bias and discrimination, skill loss and   over-reliance,   transparency   and explainability of AI algorithms, and regulation and governance. 32,33 © 2024 The Author(s).   Emergency Medicine Australasia   published by John Wiley & Sons Australia, Ltd on behalf of Australasian College for Emergency Medicine.  774   S FREEMAN   ET AL. 17426723, 2024, 5, Downloaded from https://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/10.1111/1742-6723.14449 by Cochrane Peru, Wiley Online Library on [15/04/2025]. See the Terms and Conditions (https://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/terms-and-conditions) on Wiley Online Library for rules of use; OA articles are governed by the applicable Creative Commons License\nLimitations  The   fi ndings   in   the   present   study should be considered within the con- text of its limitations. A convenience sample   was   used   to   select   partici- pants based on their accessibility and willingness to take part, which could lead   to   voluntary   response   bias.   8 Attempts   were   made   to   recruit   a sample based on demographic data provided by the Australian Institute of Health and Welfare   –   Emergency Department Activity to reduce dis- crepancies   between   the   demo- graphics   of   the   sample.   However, this was unsuccessful, leading to a sample   that   was   skewed   towards those   living   in   Victoria,   Western Australia and Queensland, those in an   older   age   bracket,   females   and those   from   a   white-Anglo   back- ground.   Additionally,   as   a   non- probability   sample,   the   results   are not representative of the Australian population.   The   grounded   theory approach also has limitations. It is accepted that using a GT approach can allow for the researcher ’ s indi- vidual   biases   and   world   view   to in fl uence study results.   34   AI is a rap- idly changing area, and the introduc- tion   and   media   coverage   of   new technologies   has   the   potential   to in fl uence   respondent   perspectives. For   example,   recent   advances   in foundation models such as ChatGPT were   released   after   the   interviews took   place,   meaning   some   health consumers ’   perspectives   may   have already changed.  Conclusion  The results discussed in this paper found that most consumers require AI to be rigorously tested and evalu- ated before it becomes operational. There is also a requirement for AI to be robustly regulated and monitored by government or a professional reg- ulatory   body   to   gain   support   and acceptance.   However,   regulation alone   is   not   considered   suf fi cient. Informed consent processes that pro- vide information about the role and functionality of AI, maintaining pri- vacy and con fi dentiality of personal health data, bias and discrimination, and the attribution of responsibility and liability for patient health out- comes are all critical issues that need to be addressed   if   AI   technologies are to be trusted and accepted by health consumers in EDs.  Acknowledgements  We thank the Consumer Community Involvement Program, Fiona Stanley Hospital Emergency Department Con- sumer Advisory Group, St Vincent ’ s Hospital Melbourne Human Research Ethics Committee layperson members, Health   Consumers   Queensland,   and the Centre for Culture, Ethnicity and Health for their support and the par- ticipants who provided feedback on our initial interview guide, who partic- ipated in the pilot interviews, and who participated in the study. Open access publishing facilitated by The Univer- sity   of   Melbourne,   as   part   of   the Wiley - The University of Melbourne agreement via the Council of Austra- lian University Librarians.  Competing interests  None declared.  Data availability statement  The de-identi fi ed data we analysed are   not   publicly   available,   but requests to the corresponding author for the data will be considered on a case-by-case basis.  References  1.   Topol E.   Deep Medicine: How Arti-  fi cial   Intelligence   Can   Make Healthcare   Human   Again   /   Eric Topol , 1st edn. New York: Basic Books, 2019. 2.   Littman   M,   Ajunwa   I,   Berger   G  et al . Gathering Strength, Gathering Storms:   The   One   Hundred   Year Study   on   Arti fi cial   Intelligence (AI100) 2021 Study Panel Report 2022. 3.   Australian Government Department of   Health   and   Aged   Care.   The Australian   Health   System: Australian Government Department of   Health   and   Aged   Care;   2019. Available from URL: https://www. health.gov.au/about-us/the-australian- health-system. 4.   Morley J, Machado CCV, Burr C  et   al .   The   ethics   of   AI   in   health care: a mapping review.   Soc. Sci. Med.   2020;   260 : 113172. 5.   Stewart J, Sprivulis P, Dwivedi G. Arti fi cial   intelligence   and   machine learning   in   emergency   medicine.  Emerg. Med. Australas.   2018;   30 : 870 – 4. 6.   Tong A, Sainsbury P, Craig J. Con- solidated criteria for reporting qual- itative   research   (COREQ):   a 32-item checklist for in