easurement Technology of the Leibniz University Hannover and is working on his Dr.-Ing degree in electrical engineering. His research activities include the improvement of ion mobility spectrometers using electric field simulations.  Moritz Hitzemann   received a B.Eng. degree in communication engineering from the University of Applied Sciences and Arts, Hannover, Germany, in 2014 and a M.Sc. degree in electrical engineering and information technology from the Leibniz University Hannover, Germany, in 2016, respectively, where he is currently pursuing the Dr.-Ing. degree with the focus on sensors and measurement technology. His current research interests include impedance measurement, microwave electronics, low power high voltage generation, high voltage switches, and ion mobility spectrometers.  Jonas Winkelholz   studied electrical engineering at the Leibniz University Hannover and graduated with an M.Sc. in 2022. Since 2022, he is employed as a research engineer at the Institute of Electrical Engineering and Measurement Technology of the Leibniz University Hannover and is working on his Dr.-Ing. degree in electrical engineering. His research interests include improving ion mobility spectrometry applications and measurement electronics like low current amplifiers, fast isolated data acquisition and processing, and high voltage switching.  David Bailey   is an aspiring student at the Leibniz University Hannover studying M.Sc. Energy Technology. He is working in the field of sensor engineering, already having gained practical experience through long-term student helper positions and successful internships. This includes developing high-voltage power sources for ion mobility spectrometer systems, analog front-end cards for the quench detection system of the superconducting magnets of the LHC at CERN, as well as full-stack monitoring and control equipment for the plasma heating systems of the innovative Wendelstein-7X fusion reactor. Currently he is finishing his Master Thesis at the Leibniz University Hannover, developing a cost- effective and sensitive ion-current amplifier for a highly integrated ion-mobility spectrometer application.  M. Lippmann et al.   HardwareX   19   (2024)   e00574  14\nStefan Zimmermann   received his diploma in electrical engineering in 1996 and his Dr.-Ing. in 2001 from the Technical University Hamburg- Harburg, Germany. In 2001, he joined the Berkeley Sensor and Actuator Center, University of California, USA, as a Postdoctoral Scientist with support of a Feodor-Lynen Fellowship of the Alexander von Humboldt Foundation. In 2004, he joined the Research Unit of Dr ¨ ager, Germany, where he worked on sensors for medical and safety applications. His latest position was Head of Chemical and Biochemical Sensors. In 2009, he joined the Leibniz University Hannover, Germany, as a Full Professor for Sensors and Measurement Technology and became Head of Department of Sensors and Measurement Technology. Since 2019, he is Director of Institute of Electrical Engineering and Measurement Technology. From 2017 to 2019, he was Vice Dean, and from 2019 to 2021, he was Dean of Faculty of Electrical Engineering and Computer Science. In 2022, he co-founded the ACKISION GmbH concentrating on advanced electronics for measuring technology.  M. Lippmann et al.   HardwareX   19   (2024)   e00574  15',0.07488928685555048,'[\"\\u0000\", \"%\", \"%)\", \"%3d%3d\", \"&\"]','2025-11-29 17:08:40.646684'),(77,3,'See discussions, stats, and author profiles for this publication at: https://www.researchgate.net/publication/380744236  Standardizing technical parameters and terms for abdominopelvic photon- counting CT: laying the groundwork for innovation and evidence sharing  Article   in   Abdominal Radiology · May 2024  DOI: 10.1007/s00261-024-04342-4  CITATIONS  4  READS  99  10 authors , including:  Safa Hoodeshenas  Mayo Foundation for Medical Education and Research  20   PUBLICATIONS   260   CITATIONS  SEE PROFILE  Yoad Yagil  Philips  60   PUBLICATIONS   2,353   CITATIONS  SEE PROFILE  Francis I Baffour  Mayo Clinic - Rochester  69   PUBLICATIONS   1,436   CITATIONS  SEE PROFILE  Joel G Fletcher  Mayo Foundation for Medical Education and Research  534   PUBLICATIONS   27,140   CITATIONS  SEE PROFILE  All content following this page was uploaded by Safa Hoodeshenas on 30 June 2024.  The user has requested enhancement of the downloaded file.\nVol.:(0123456789) Abdominal Radiology https://doi.org/10.1007/s00261-024-04342-4  PERSPECTIVE FROM THE SAR  Standardizing technical parameters and terms for abdominopelvic photon‑counting CT: laying the groundwork for innovation and evidence sharing  Shuai Leng 1   · Giuseppe V. Toia 2   · Safa Hoodeshenas 1   · Juan Carlos Ramirez‑Giraldo 3   · Yoad Yagil   4   · Jonathan S. Maltz   5   · Kirsten Boedeker   6   · Ke Li 2   · Francis Baffour 1   · Joel G. Fletcher 1  Received: 1 March 2024 / Revised: 11 April 2024 / Accepted: 15 April 2024 © The Author(s), under exclusive licence to Springer Science+Business Media, LLC, part of Springer Nature 2024  Abstract  Photon-counting detector CT (PCD-CT) is a new technology that has multiple diagnostic benefits including increased spatial resolution, iodine signal, and radiation dose efficiency, as well as multi-energy imaging capability, but which also has unique challenges in abdominal imaging. The purpose of this work is to summarize key features, technical parameters, and terms, which are common amongst current abdominopelvic PCD-CT systems and to propose standardized terminology (where none exists). In addition, user-selectable protocol parameters are highlighted to facilitate both scientific evaluation and early clinical adoption. Unique features of PCD-CT systems include photon-counting detectors themselves, energy thresholds and bins, and tube potential considerations for preserved spectral separation. Key parameters for describing different PCD-CT systems are reviewed and explained. While PCD-CT can generate multi-energy images like dual-energy CT, there are new types of images such as threshold images, energy bin images, and special spectral images. The standardized terms and con- cepts herein build upon prior interdisciplinary consensus and have been endorsed by the newly created Society of Abdominal Radiology Photon-counting CT Emerging Technology Commission.  Keywords   Computed tomography · X-ray · Photons · Humans · Radiation dosage · Abdomen · Standardization  Introduction  Conventional energy-integrating detectors (EID) of com- puted tomography (CT) convert X-ray photons to visible light through scintillation and record the sum of ener- gies deposited by all photons using light sensors, charge integrators, and analog-to-digital converters. Photon-count- ing detector CT (PCD-CT) is a relatively new CT technology in which the energy of each individual photon is directly converted to an electrical signal and recorded by the X-ray detector [1, 2]. In the last 20 years, the speed at which PCDs can count photons has advanced several orders of magnitude, from the low fluxes encountered in their classical application in nuclear medicine to the massive maximum flux of clinical CT. The first FDA-cleared PCD-CT system was released in 2021. A substantial body of literature demonstrates the potential of PCD-CT, both commercial product and proto- type systems, to achieve high spatial resolution and spectral imaging, as well as reduction in patient radiation dose and injected iodinated contrast dose [2–12]. PCD systems achieve substantial improvements in spatial resolution over conventional EID-CTs (with the exception of specialized high resolution systems [13, 14]) in neuro- radiology, thoracic, cardiac, and musculoskeletal radiol- ogy [8, 15–21], with distinct and readily apparent advan- tages of multi-energy PCD images also demonstrated in  *   Joel G. Fletcher  Fletcher.Joel@mayo.edu 1   Department of Radiology, Mayo Clinic, 200 First Street SW, Rochester, MN 55905, USA 2   Departments of Radiology and Medical Physics, University of Wisconsin School of Medicine and Public Health, Madison, WI, USA 3   Siemens Medical Solutions USA Inc, Malvern, PA, USA 4   PD CT/AMI R&D Advanced Development, Philips Medical Systems, Haifa, Israel 5   Molecular Imaging and Computed Tomography, GE Healthcare, Waukesha, WI, USA 6   Canon Medical Systems Corporation, Otawara, Japan\nAbdominal Radiology  cardiovascular imaging (e.g., for imaging of the coronary arteries and other small vessels) [8, 22, 23]). To avoid optical crosstalk, each scintillator pixel in an EID-CT detector is optically isolated from its neighbors by thin septa. This creates dead zones that cannot generate an optical signal. In contrast, detector pixels of PCDs directly generate electron–hole pairs without the intermediate step involving visible light, which eliminates the need for physi- cal septa. An EID-CT system with the same pixel pitch (i.e., distance between the center of two adjacent detector pixels) could achieve the same spatial resolution but would require a larger dose to attain an equal image contrast-to-noise ratio (CNR) for a given acquisition and reconstruction approach. PCD-CT does have its unique challenges, including both technical and practical challenges, such as pileup, charge sharing, sensor material polarization, and -fluorescence escapes [2, 4, 5, 12, 24]. Pileup occurs when more than one photon contributes to a single counting time window. Detector response is non-linear due to pileup, starting with weak non-linearity at low flux levels and up to saturation at extremely high flux levels. It can lead to errors in the pho- ton count, and errors in the measured photon energy; pileup compromises image accuracy, increases noise, and corrupts spectral information. Charge sharing, K-escape, and Comp- ton scatter within the detector increase image noise, compro- mise spatial resolution, and degrade spectral performance. Various proposed techniques, such as calibration and correc- tion, as well as selection of detector pixel size, are utilized to mitigate these challenges. In PCD-CT, a given dose pro- vides a fixed number of photons that are distributed across more pixels and energy bins, leading to a lower number of counts in each spatial-spectral bin when highly attenuating anatomies such as the abdomen are imaged. Preserving the ultra-high-resolution of the detection in the reconstructed CT image requires using sharp image reconstruction filters. As a consequence, advanced approaches to noise manage- ment are required, and ultra-high-resolution PCD-CT modes might need to sacrifice some spatial and spectral information [2, 25, 26]. In addition, there are some practical, workflow-related challenges. PCDs generate massive amounts of raw data rel- ative to conventional-resolution EID systems, since counts are collected from many more (smaller) pixels, and multi- ple energy bins per pixel. Large matrix sizes are typically needed to support the high-resolution images. Finer slice thicknesses (and smaller increments) generate more image slices. These can increase reader burden and challenge the capacity of data transfer and storage infrastructure unless carefully managed. While several studies have shown improved image quality for routine and multi-energy images, iodine contrast, CNR, and reduced radiation dose for a variety of abdominopel- vic CT applications [27–29], performance improvement for diagnostic tasks in abdominopelvic CT is in its early stages. Diagnostic tasks in abdominopelvic CT pose several chal- lenges for radiologists: principally, highly attenuating body regions, large volume of coverage, and the diagnostic impor- tance of low contrast detection (e.g., pancreatic, and primary and secondary hepatic malignancies). Moreover, as PCD-CT systems are installed in radiology practices (including aca- demic practices), diagnostic tasks for which there is already early evidence of clear patient benefit (e.g., CSF-venous fistulas, temporal bone imaging, small vessel CT angiog- raphy, coronary angiography, interstitial lung disease) [18, 20, 21, 30–33] may be prioritized over abdominal protocols where patient benefit may be less obvious. Consequently, the abdominal imaging community will need to work col- laboratively across institutions to speed translational devel- opment in GI and GU imaging PCD clinical applications. This necessity will only increase as more PCD-CT systems become available from other CT manufacturers [34]. The purpose of this manuscript is to summarize existing technical parameters and terms used in PCD-CT protocols and propose standardized terminology (where none exists) as well as to highlight user-selectable protocol parameters to facilitate both scientific evaluation across institutions and early clinical adoption for patient care.  Methods  In February 2023, 15 abdominal radiologists and 7 CT physicists met to discuss the possibility of the Society of Abdominal Radiology (SAR) forming a PCD-CT Emerg- ing Technology Commission (ETC). The CT physicists present were from multiple academic medical centers and CT manufacturers. An early priority for this group was to establish common terminology that could be used across current and future PCD-CT systems and manufacturers. Drs. Bari Dane from New York University and Daniele Marin from Duke University were selected to lead the nascent PCD-CT ETC and assigned the current authors to propose standardized terms and protocol element requirements for communications. The author group subsequently examined the work of the DICOM Standards Committee (Supplement 188, WG-21: Computed Tomography), the American Association of Physicists in Medicine CT Lexicon 2.0, as well the consen- sus society recommendations for standardized terminology for cardiac CT [35–38]. Existing photon-counting detector technologies and the ones currently in development were reviewed, as well as parameters used to describe the techni- cal features and performance of the current FDA-cleared PCD-CT systems [1, 39]. Co-authors included scientists from each of the four PCD-CT systems that image the abdomen and pelvis. The proposed terminology was refined\nAbdominal Radiology  through an iterative process of multiple drafts and confer- ence calls, and amended as shared understanding developed. It was approved by all authors in consensus. A confidential draft was shared with members of the full SAR PCD ETC, who endorsed the document, and provided feedback to the authors for improvement.  Results  X‑ray detectors  There are many similarities between PCD-CT and EID-CT systems, and for a given CT system model/design, the major difference is the detector itself (Fig. 1). We discuss a few important parameters of PCD-CT systems. The X-ray detector is one of the main components of a CT scanner. X-ray detectors are classified into two main categories, indirect and direct systems, depending on their method of converting X-ray photons into electrical signals. Furthermore, they may vary in terms of signal processing techniques using readout electronics (e.g., integrating and counting technologies). The prevailing sensor materials uti- lized in PCDs are semiconductors such as cadmium tellu- ride (CdTe), cadmium zinc telluride (CZT), or silicon (Si), although other substances such as gallium arsenide have also been employed (Table 1) [40–43]. Sensor materials used in EIDs include cadmium tungstate, gadolinium oxide, gado- linium oxysulfide, lutetium aluminum terbium garnet [44], and other fast scintillators. Smaller detector cell size implies a higher spatial sam- pling rate, allowing reconstruction of thinner slices with higher in-plane resolution. Even when high spatial resolu- tion is not required, inherent high sampling rates may reduce aliasing of high frequency noise into the image signal, and this in turn reduces image noise [39, 45, 46]. However, when high resolution is indeed the clinical objective, image noise must be appropriately controlled through iterative reconstruction, deep learning reconstruction, or alternative denoising strategies [39, 45–47]. To reconstruct images with higher spatial resolution, radiologists also should under- stand that other image reconstruction parameters need to be changed appropriately (e.g., thinner slices, sharper recon- struction kernels, higher image matrix; Fig. 2).  Thresholds, energy bins, tube potentials, and automatic exposure control  The lowest energy threshold of a PCD is usually set to eliminate electronic noise, e.g., 20–30 keV for the CdTe/  Fig.   1   Schematic illustration of the operational principles of energy integrating and photon counting detectors.   A   In the EID technology, poly energetic X-ray photons are initially captured by a scintillator, which converts the X-ray photon energy into visible light. The light photons are then transformed into electrical signals by a pixelated photodiode. These electrical signals are integrated to produce an out- put signal that directly corresponds to the total energy of the detected photons. Integration of electrical signals occurs during a single CT projection, with scintillation being a long process compared to ( B ). Scintillation and integration consequently result in down-weighting of signal from low energy photons, which carry important biologic information.   B   In the PCD technology, the semiconductor layer directly converts X-ray photons into electron–hole pairs. Applying a high voltage (800–1000 V) induces the electrons and holes to drift towards two opposite directions, generating electrical current .   Each detected signal is categorized into specific bins based on their respec- tive magnitudes. Conversion of incident photons to electrical signal takes only a few nanoseconds, so the energy corresponding to each photon is individually counted\nAbdominal Radiology  CZT-based systems, and is set to a lower keV for silicon- based systems [48, 49]. The energy thresholds of the remain- ing bins can be set to create two or more energy bins. PCDs assign incident photons to bins based on the measured pho- ton energy being between the two thresholds that define a bin (Table 2) [9]. The signal within each energy bin can then be used to create the multi-energy images which are similar to dual-energy CT (Fig. 3 [50]; see   Image Reconstruction , below). The specific values of the lower and higher energy thresholds may vary for different tasks, and for different tube potential and filtration settings, and are either predetermined by the manufacturer or may be adjusted by the user. The tube potential refers to the electron acceleration voltage in the X-ray tube. In CT, the tube potentials are  Table   1   Existing, prototype, or in-development PCD systems by different CT manufacturers, which image the abdomen and pelvis. Adapted and updated, with permission, from [40]. Detector pixel size is given at the isocenter. Parameters were reported to authors by scientists from each CT manufacturer a   ASIC   Application-specific integrated circuit b   Not available c   FDA-approved clinical CT system Sensor material   Sensor thickness   Pixel size at isocenter   [mm   2   ]   ASIC   a Energy bins  Siemens healthineers c   CdTe   1.6 mm   0.151   ×   0.176 (sub- pixel)/0.302   ×   0.352 (macropixel) 4  GE healthcare   [42]   Si   >   30 mm   NA b   8  Philips   CZT   2 mm   0.27   ×   0.27   5  Canon   [43]   CZT   NA b   0.2   ×   0.2   6  Fig.   2   Axial images from a PCD-CT angiography in a 75 year-old male patient with a fenestrated aortic stent graft illustrate how spatial resolution can be improve by adjusting image reconstruction param- eters. Spatial resolution and image sharpness increase with thinner slice thickness, sharper reconstruction kernel (designated by higher numbers), and larger image matrix (e.g., 1024 vs. 512).   A   3 mm slice, Qr40 reconstruction kernel (Threshold Low, 120 kV), 512 matrix;   B  1 mm slice, Qr40 reconstruction kernel, 512 matrix (Threshold Low, 120 kV);   C   1 mm slice, Bv60 reconstruction kernel (at 67 keV), 512 matrix;   D   1 mm slice, Bv60 reconstruction kernel (at 67 keV), 1024 matrix;   E   0.6 mm slice, Bv72 reconstruction kernel (at 67 keV), 1024 matrix. The Bv kernels (e.g., Bv60) have edge enhancement, which are used for vascular reconstructions. The Qr kernels in figure parts A and B are quantitative kernels that don’t have edge enhancement. Qr kernels provide accurate CT numbers and are commonly used in multi-energy processing, e.g., material decomposition. The mean energy for the 120 kV tube potential is 67 keV, so the iodine signal response from the detector will be similar between the Threshold Low images ( A   and   B ) and the 67 keV virtual monoenergetic images ( C–E )\nAbdominal Radiology  typically in the range of 70–150 kV. Tube potential is determined by the user and scanner depending upon the diagnostic task (Table 2). Lower tube potentials are often used for single energy EID-CT (SECT) contrast-enhanced exams to reduce radiation dose and increase iodine sig- nal, based on patient size and diagnostic task, with higher tube potentials reducing iodine signal and image noise, but often needed for larger patients. For dual-energy EID- CT, a high and a low x-ray tube potential are utilized to obtain the needed separation of photon energies needed to produce multi-energy images. At PCD-CT, the photon- counting detector itself improves iodine signal thereby facilitating the use of higher tube potentials, which also possess the wider spectrum of photon energies needed for multi-energy imaging. Virtual monoenergetic images (VMI) can be created at dual-energy CT and PCD -CT to simulate the appearance of a CT image at a specific mono- chromatic x-ray beam energy. Low energy keV VMIs (e.g., 40–60 keV images) enable significant increase in iodine contrast and CNR beyond conventional single energy low kV scan [51, 52], and are created at PCD from a single tube potential.  Table   2   Terms for detectors and Energy Thresholds a   User-selectable parameter Recommended Term   Explanation/Comment Energy-integrating detectors (EID)   A scintillating detector that first transforms incident X-ray photons to visible light and then into electric signals, measuring total energy deposited by all photons incident within a given integration period Photon-counting detector (PCD)   A semiconductor detector that directly transfers incident X-ray photons into electron–hole pairs, counts the number of photons, and measures each photon’s energy Multilayer detector (MLD)   More than one physical detector sensor layer to simultaneously collect different energy level data of the X-ray spectrum Energy   threshold a   A predetermined level of energy, in units of keV, used as a reference point for energy binning. This may or may not be selectable by users, depending on the system and/or protocol. Thresholds between different PCD systems may be different, as these are optimized for each PCD system. Low energy threshold   Set to eliminate electronic noise below this threshold; (e.g., 20 or 25 keV for cadmium telluride or CZT PCDs) Energy bin   A specific range of energy levels defined by a lower energy threshold and a higher energy threshold Detector pixel   Size of a single detector unit, usually rectangular in shape. Note that the length and width of a detector pixel may be different corresponding to different in-plane and z resolutions. Alternative terms previously used include detector cells and detector elements. Detector coverage   The dimension of the exposed detector rows along the z-axis, expressed in millimeters at the isocenter Pulse   An abrupt and temporary variation in the amplitude of an electric signal generated when X-ray photon interacts with the PCD Pulse shaping   The process of altering the waveform of a signal to attain desired characteristics. This is a necessary step creating final recorded signal on PCD. Tube   potential a   The electron acceleration voltage of the X-ray tube. Lower tube potentials increase iodine signal and decrease radiation dose, but may limit multi-energy options due to decrease spectral separation. Tube filtration   Filtration refers to materials placed in front of the X-ray tube to change the X-ray spectrum, and are listed with the tube potential (e.g., 100 kV/Sn refers to use of a tin filter with 100 kV X-ray beam, a common combination to reduce radiation dose for unenhanced CT scans). Collimation a   Refers to the grouping of detector pixels along the z direction during data acquisition, usually lists the number of detectors along the z direction and their pixel size (at iso center; e.g., 120   ×   0.2 mm). Refers to the detector at isocenter  Fig.   3   Sample illustration of threshold images (TL, TH) and bin images (B1, B2) of a PCD-CT with 140   kV and 25 and 65   keV thresholds. (Adapted and reprinted, with permission, from [50])\nAbdominal Radiology  To achieve sufficient spectral separation, PCD-CT com- monly utilizes higher tube potentials such as 120 or 140 kV for multi-energy applications. This selection helps reduce image noise and produce more accurate material quantifi- cation, all of which also permit high quality virtual mono- energetic and other multi-energy images (Fig. 4), similar to those obtained using dual-energy CT systems [53]. For unenhanced scans without a strong need for multi-energy capability, lower kVs with additional beam filtration (e.g., 100 kV with tin filtration) may be used to lower radiation dose [54]. Automatic exposure control (AEC) is a tool which adjusts tube current to produce reliable image quality and reduce radiation dose. Specific implementations of AEC vary among CT vendors. The current FDA-cleared PCD-CT sys- tem automatically selects the appropriate VMI energy level (keV) for a user-selected diagnostic task and image quality requirement as part of the AEC. Tasks such as CT angi- ography can be optimized by selecting lower VMI energy levels (e.g., 55 keV), which facilitate higher levels of iodine contrast and can result in greater levels of radiation dose reduction.  CT system description  There are many key parameters for describing PCD-CT sys- tems (Tables 2 and 3). •   Energy threshold selection   (Table 2): These may be pre-fixed by the vendors (specific values) or selectable by the users (with limited range for each energy thresh- old). The selection of energy thresholds substantially impacts the image quality of multi-energy (multi-mate- rial) images. Optimal energy threshold selection depends on tube potential, beam filtration, PCD sensor material (e.g., CdTe, CZT, or silicon), patient size, and imaging tasks. Unlike multi-energy EID-CT whose spectra are essentially pre-determined, PCD-CT has the capability to freely select energy thresholds. With this flexibility, K-edge imaging, a technique where energy thresholds are  Fig.   4   Axial   PCD   CT   images   obtained   in   the   portal   phase   of enhancement used to characterize a right renal mass in a 75 year-old male (undergoing an exam for liver cirrhosis, which did not detect a liver mass) illustrate typical multi-energy images used at PCD, which are similar to dual-energy CT. Detector configuration was 144   ×   0.4 mm to obtain coverage of the entire abdomen and pelvis. Matrix size was set at 768   ×   768, and slice thickness was 3 mm for all reconstructions.   A   120 kV Threshold Low image;   B   67 keV virtual monoenergetic image (same window-level as [ A ]);   C   50 keV virtual monoenergetic image (inset with same window-level as figure parts  A   and   B );   D   virtual non-contrast image (VNC),   E   iodine map. Using these multi-energy images, the mass was diagnosed as a renal neo- plasm. Note that the 120 kV Threshold Low image and the 67 keV image are identical, as the mean tube energy for the CT system (NAEOTOM Alpha, Siemens Healthineers) is 67 keV. Note increased iodine signal on the 50 keV and iodine map images compared to the VNC, Threshold Low, and 67 keV image\nAbdominal Radiology  set close to the K-edge energies of the relevant material, for example ≈50 keV for Gd [55, 56], has been demon- strated. •   Detector pixel size   (Table 3) [38, 57]: A major benefit of PCD-CT is high spatial resolution. The detector pixel is usually smaller than that of EID-CT. The main consid- erations in selecting pixel size include spatial resolution, spectral performance, and pulse pileup. Small pixels have compromised spectral performance due to charge shar- ing and K-fluorescence escapes. Large pixels are more susceptible to pileup. Spatial resolution improves with smaller pixels as long as the focal spot size is not the limiting factor. When large anatomies are imaged using commercial PCD-CT systems, the higher mA values needed may require the use of larger focal spot sizes, which may limit the spatial resolution that can be realized by the system. •   Detector pixel configuration : In addition to the native detector pixel size, some PCD-CT systems allow bin- ning of detector pixels to form larger pixel sizes. This is useful when the ultra-high resolution (UHR) mode of the PCD-CT is not required to execute a clinical task. It is important to note that utilizing UHR requires large image matrix sizes and thin slices, expanding the size of image series. For example, for large body regions such as the abdomen and pelvis, it may be advantageous to use larger pixel sizes and reconstruct regular or modestly larger matrix sizes. •   X-ray focal spot : To exploit UHR modes, a small focal spot is needed so that the system resolution is not lim- ited by the focal spot size. However, a small focal spot implies a lower maximum tube power. Some CT systems can adapt focal spot size based on the mA required. In clinical practice, focal spot size and spatial resolution may need to be balanced to permit sufficiently fast scans and good temporal resolution. It is important to note that UHR and temporal resolution are closely related as UHR images may display small motion artifacts such as minimal organ displacement beyond regular cardiac and respiratory motion. •   Scan mode:   As in EID-CT, axial and helical/spiral modes are available in PCD-CT. For PCD-CT scanners with two source-detector systems, a high-pitch helical mode is also available. •   Detector Operation Mode : In addition to scan mode, there are other considerations in PCD-CT, especially regarding high resolution and multi-energy capabili- ties, e.g., UHR mode and multi-energy mode. These are  Table   3   Terms used to describe CT systems other than X-ray detectors. Many of these terms are taken or adapted from a prior interdisciplinary consensus statement [38] a   User-selectable parameter Recommended Term   Explanation/Comment Scan   mode a   Axial/sequential, helical/spiral, or high-pitch helical. These terms can be applied to EID or PCD CT systems. Detector operation   mode a   Includes other image acquisition factors for PCD-CT, especially regarding high resolution and multi- energy capabilities, e.g., UHR mode and multi-energy mode. Selection of energy thresholds and   bins a   The selection of energy thresholds substantially impacts the image quality of multi-energy images. They may be pre-fixed by the vendors (specific values) or adjustable by the users (specific range for each energy threshold). The optimal energy threshold selection depends on tube potential, PCD sen- sor material (e.g., CdTe, CZT, or silicon), and imaging tasks. Ultra-high resolution (UHR) a   UHR is not well-defined and varies between CT systems and manufacturers. Spatial resolution away from isocenter is often reduced, and depends on many factors other than the detector such as focal spot size. Given its inconsistent use, authors should define how the term UHR is used in each scien- tific or review article. X-ray focal   spot   a   To accommodate the high spatial resolution in UHR mode, a small focal spot is needed so that the system resolution will not be limited by focal spot size. However, small focal spot size comes with lower tube power. Focal spot size may be associated with scan mode, may or may not be selectable by users. Some CT systems may have adaptive focal spots, e.g., using small focal spot for low mA and large focal spot when mA goes beyond a certain limit. Dual-source High   pitch a This is defined only for dual-source CT systems and is not available with single source CT systems. It refers to the ability to use two X-ray tubes to increase table speeds with pitch as high as 3.2/3.4 by using a second X-ray tube to obtain overlapping projection data (i.e., the projection data for either tube is non-overlapping) [57]. The upper limit of pitch for most single source CT systems is about 1.7. Detector pixel size   Detector pixel size has a major role in image resolution and refers to the size (e.g., length and width) of a single detector unit, commonly in rectangular shape. Note that pixel size sometimes refers to the detector physical size and sometimes to its projection at the iso center, which is typically 1.6–2 times smaller than the physical size.\nAbdominal Radiology  referred to as detector operation modes. Note that these may be called scan mode for certain manufacturers. With the unique capability of the PCD-CT, there might be new scan mode that is not feasible with EID-CT, e.g., the high-pitch, multi-energy mode [58]. •   Collimation : As with conventional EID-CT systems, different modes of operation of PCD-CT systems may offer different X-ray beam collimation configurations. As PCD-CT generates significantly more data compared to EID-CT in similar configurations, the minimal detec- tor configuration needs to be balanced against the table speed (e.g., to cover an anatomic region) or desired radia- tion dose.  Image types  The intrinsic multi-energy capability of PCD-CT allows the generation of a variety of spectral images (Table 4; Figs. 4  Table   4   Image Types in PCD-CT a   User-selectable parameter Recommended Term   Explanation/Comment Threshold image   The image uses photon energies above an energy threshold at the selected tube potential. For example, in a PCD-CT with 2 energy thresholds of 25 and 65 keV, two threshold images (low:   >   25 keV and high:   >   65 keV) can be generated (Fig. 3). The threshold low image is similar to that of standard single-energy images in EID-CT, though with equal photon weight- ing instead of energy weighting and with electronic noise removed. With the current FDA- approved system, the threshold low image is similar to the 67 keV image. Bin image   Data between two energy thresholds (or the highest threshold and the tube potential) can be used to generate energy bin images. Note that, additional processes might be conducted dur- ing the reconstruction of bin images, e.g., decorrelation. For example, high energy bin images with the current FDA-approved system, would be created from photon energies greater than 65 keV, and might be used clinically to reduce beam-hardening from metal (similar to a high energy VMI), as the photons creating the image would be higher energies. A higher level of iterative reconstruction might be chosen with the bin energy bin image to reduce the image noise in this instance, as the image would represent a fraction of the radiation dose. Virtual monoenergetic image (VMI) a   The image is reconstructed to resemble one obtained with a monoenergetic beam. Iodine   map a   A material selective image composed of iodine-equivalent signals Iodine   overlay a   An image with iodine map (in color) overlaid on standard CT images (grayscale) Virtual non-contrast (VNC) a   The image after iodine-equivalent signal has been removed from the original image Virtual non-calcium (VNCa) a   The image after calcium-equivalent signal has been removed from the original image Electron density   image a   The image representing the spatial distribution of the material electron densities. Its pixel value is usually normalized to water electron density. Effective atomic number image   (Z eff ) [59–61]: a   The image representing the spatial distribution of the effective atomic number.   Z eff   values may vary between CT systems due to differences in the definition of   Z eff Material specific   image a   This category of images represents the distribution of certain materials, e.g., iodine map. The images are commonly in the unit of mass density, e.g., mg/cc. PCD-CT enables additional classes of material specific images: k-edge images. For example, Gadolinium, Ytterbium, Tantalum, Tungsten, Gold, and Bismuth, all have a sharp k-edge within the X-ray spectrum. Special spectral image (SSI) formats   These special image formats save basic information needed for spectral post-processing, such as creating VMIs, iodine maps, and VNC images, with names and formats varying by manufac- turer. These images allow users to perform multi-energy processing on demand, which could potentially enhance workflow and efficiency. For multiinstitutional studies, SSI image formats are critical to save so that similar multi-energy images can be created between institutions. They may be useful in clinical practice, as they permit the generation of additional multi- energy images that may be helpful for lesion characterization. Material removal   images a   These are images after certain material(s) have been digitally removed from the original images, e.g., virtual non-contrast (VNC), virtual non-calcium (VNCa), virtual unenhanced (VUE). For example, contribution of certain materials can be removed from the final images after material decomposition. Material-modified   image a   Images with altered pixel values to highlight or suppress a target   material 29   (e.g., gout, tendon). Material-modified images are sometimes called “material-enhanced” images). Unlike material specific images, which represent quantity of certain materials, the material-modified images alter pixel values to highlight certain material or tissue rather than reflecting true density or concentration.\nAbdominal Radiology  and 5) [59–61]. Many of the spectral imaging outputs by PCD-CTs, such as VMIs, virtual non-contrast (VNC), iodine overlay, or iodine map images are familiar to dual-energy CT users. •   Threshold (counting) images:   Threshold (or count- ing) images use all photons over the pre-defined energy thresholds. For example, in a PCD-CT with 2 energy thresholds at 25 and 65 keV with a tube potential of 140   kV, two threshold images (low:   >   25   keV and high:   >   65 keV) can be generated (Fig. 3). The thresh- old low image (called a “T3D” image using the FDA- approved PCD-CT system) is analogous to a standard single-energy image in EID-CT, though with the con- tributions of all photons weighted equally, rather than favoring photons with higher energy. •   Energy bin images:   These images are reconstructed using only those photons having energies that lie between two energy thresholds (or between the highest thresh- old and the tube potential). In the example above, Bin 1 (25–65 keV) and Bin 2 (65–140 keV) images can be created. •   Special spectral images (SSI) : These images save basic information needed for spectral post-processing performed at a later time (on demand), such as creating VMIs, iodine maps, and VNC images. Examples include spectral base image (SBI, Philips Medical Systems), spectral post-processing (SPP, Siemens Healthineers), and MegaMONOS (GE Healthcare). These images allow users to perform multi-energy processing on demand, which potentially enhances workflow and efficiency. For multi-institutional studies, SSI image formats are criti- cal so that similar multi-energy images can be created between institutions. They are useful in clinical practice, as they permit generation of additional multi-energy images that may be helpful for lesion characterization. •   Virtual monoenergetic images (VMIs) : Like dual- energy CT, VMIs from PCD-CT represent images as if they were acquired with a monoenergetic X-ray beam. One of the advantages of PCD-CT is that VMIs may be the primary image type interpreted. VMIs are commonly used in dual-energy CT clinical practice, e.g., 50 keV images are commonly used clinically to potentiate iodine signal, while 70 keV images generally optimize aspects of image quality by exhibiting lower noise [62]. As an initial first step, these VMI energy levels are recom- mended for PCD-CT, although the exact keV values may vary with manufacturer and clinical practice. In conven- tional single-energy CT, the CT number (HU) of the same material can vary among different scanner models (same vendor or different vendors) due to the spectra dif- ference from X-ray tube and filters. Since VMI represents images at a given energy level (keV), the CT numbers at this level are fundamentally determined, independent of scanners or vendors from a theoretical point of view. Therefore, VMI images should provide more consistent Hounsfield unit values across different CT models and manufacturers, although in practice the accuracy of CT numbers may depend on specific implementations. Their  Fig.   5   Rubric for naming of multi-energy images (see Classification of multi-energy images from DICOM supplement 188, line 100). Blue refers to different image types. Green refers to classes of material quantification images\nAbdominal Radiology  use in radiomics and multicenter studies is considered advantageous [63–67]. •   Material-specific images : These images represent the spatial distribution of certain materials such as iodine or calcium. The images are commonly in the unit of density, e.g., mg/cc. •   Material removal images : In these images, certain material(s) have been digitally removed from the original images, e.g., VNC, virtual non-calcium (VNCa), virtual unenhanced (VUE), water no iodine, and iodine no water. K-edge imaging is a unique capability of PCD-CT due to its flexibility to select energy thresholds right below and/or above the K-edge of certain materials. K-edge images are a type of material specific images. Potential applications include the imaging of new contrast agents (e.g., gold, bismuth, and gadolinium) with detectable K-edge in the typical energy range of X-ray imaging, and the simultaneous use of two or more contrast agents. K-edge imaging is not yet in clinical use for in vivo patient imaging but has been demonstrated in research studies using prototype systems and animal studies. Table 5 lists image reconstruction parameters that reflect spatial resolution, image noise, and noise texture (i.e., noise power spectrum).  Description of PCD‑CT protocols  In multi-center collaborations or clinical trials, it is critical to have consistent imaging protocols. To ensure this, key ele- ments need to be determined while sharing protocols among different institutes. Key elements that are important for PCD-CT abdominal protocols are summarized in Table 6. Most of these are generally applicable to all PCD-CT sys- tems. At the time when this report is written, only one com- mercial PCD-CT is available that can perform abdominal CT scans. Therefore, some of the protocol elements described might be specific to this system.  Discussion  This paper provides a brief review of PCD-CT technology and its challenges from the perspective of multiple CT manufac- turers as well as subspecialized radiologists and builds upon prior interdisciplinary consensus regarding the use of PCD-CT terminology and extends it for abdominopelvic imaging. The terms and standards set forth in the text and tables have been endorsed by the   Society of Abdominal Radiology’s Emerging Technology Commission on Photon-counting CT . Standard- ized use of accepted terms will facilitate rapid adoption of this exciting new technology for individual hospitals and clinics, and rapid innovation within our subspecialty, as we seek to improve radiologist performance for existing diagnostic tasks in abdominopelvic CT, continue to lower radiations dose, and  Table   5   Image reconstruction parameters that reflect spatial resolution, image noise, and noise texture a   User-selectable parameter Image Reconstruction Parameter   Definition/Comment Reconstruction   algorithm a   Algorithm used to convert CT projection data into a tomographic image. Common algorithms include filtered backprojection (FBP), iterative reconstruction (IR), and deep learning reconstruction. Filtered back projection (FBP)   An analytical image reconstruction algorithm, with closed form formula and fast reconstruction speed, but suboptimal image noise properties. Iterative   reconstruction a   A reconstruction algorithm that iteratively updates images until a target objective function is achieved. It can be raw data based, image based, or based on hybrid methods. Deep learning reconstruction   Image reconstruction based on deep neural network, especially convolutional neural network (CNN). Training could include high quality patient and/or phantom data, including raw data and/or images. Reconstruction strength   setting a   For iterative reconstruction and deep learning reconstruction, different strength settings are commonly avail- able for users, which impact appearance of images with balance among resolution, noise, and texture. Typi- cally, these strength settings range from 1 to 4 or 5. Reconstruction   Kernel a   Reconstruction property that determines noise level, noise texture, and sharpness of the images in the axial plane [36] Matrix   size a   Size of the matrix used to store each reconstructed CT image, e.g., 512   ×   512, 1024   ×   1024, etc. 512   ×   512 is the typical matrix size for EID-CT images. Noise reduction   algorithm a   An algorithm applied by the vendor as part of image reconstruction to reduce image noise. Algorithms may operate on image or projection data. Slice thickness/increment   a   Nominal thickness of images and distance between two consecutive slices, respectively Field of view (FOV) a   The size of the reconstructed image Recon   plane a   Axial, sagittal, coronal, and oblique\nAbdominal Radiology  develop and validate new diagnostic tasks and information not available with conventional CT systems.  Supplementary Information   The online version contains supplemen- tary material available at https:// doi. org/ 10. 1007/ s00261- 024- 04342-4.  Acknowledgements   The authors wish to thank Mr. Kevin Kimlinger for editorial assistance in compiling and submitting the manuscript.  Author contributions   All authors have reviewed and approved the final document and provided editorial input and met all ICJME requirements for authorship.  Funding   None.  Data availability   N/A.  Declarations  Competing interests   Juan Carlos Ramirez-Giraldo is an employee of Siemens Healthineers. Yoad Yagil is an employee of Philips Health- care. Jonathan Maltz is an employee of GE Healthcare. Kirsten Boede- ker is an employee of Canon Medical Systems. Joel G. Fletcher is the recipient of a research grant to his institution from Siemens Health- ineers, unrelated to this work. Giuseppe Toia is an independent consult- ant for GE Healthcare and Canon Medical on topics unrelated to the content of our work.  Ethical approval   None required—Perspective paper.  Informed Consent   None required—Perspective paper.  References  1.   Rajendran K, Petersilka M, Henning A et al (2022) First Clini- cal Photon-counting Detector CT System: Technical Evaluation. Radiology 303:130-138  2.   Leng S, Bruesewitz M, Tao S et al (2019) Photon-counting Detec- tor CT: System Design and Clinical Applications of an Emerging Technology. Radiographics 39:729-743  3.   Baffour FI, Glazebrook KN, Ferrero A et al (2023) Photon-Count- ing Detector CT for Musculoskeletal Imaging: A Clinical Perspec- tive. AJR Am J Roentgenol 220:551-560  4.   Danielsson M, Persson M, Sjolin M (2021) Photon-counting x-ray detectors for CT. Phys Med B